r 1439","1480":"1480","1547":"1547","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1414":"1414","abt 1447":"about 1447","1422":"1422","1453":"1453","1464":"1464","1397":"1397","1430":"1430","1429":"1429","1439":"1439","Sheen Place, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Little Wenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Little Wenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Heath","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Haith","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): variant of   Heath  ."]},{"name":"Heathman","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a dweller ‘on the heath’, from Middle English <i>he(a)th</i> + <i>man(ne)</i>. Compare   Heath   and   Heather  ."]},{"name":"Hatton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."]},{"name":"Heather","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a ‘dweller on the heath’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>hethe</i>; compare   Heath  . The name may also be habitational name from Heather (Leicestershire), from Old English <i>hǣthor</i> ‘heathland’ (<i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + the noun suffix <i>-or</i>) or <i>hǣddre</i> ‘heather’. This surname is widespread in southern England, and also established in Ireland."]},{"name":"Health","meanings":["(1997: 105;2010: NA)","Altered form of English and Scottish   Heath  .","English and Scottish: perhaps a nickname from the vocabulary word <i>health</i>. — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is 105."]},{"name":"Hoad","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, from Middle English <i>hoth</i> ‘heath’ (Old English <i>hāth</i>, a byform of Old English <i>hǣth</i>), or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Hoath in Kent. This form was restricted in the Middle Ages to southeastern England, and the surname is still largely confined to Kent, Surrey, and Sussex. Compare   Heath  ."]},{"name":"Heid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Eckhart, Gerd, Gotthilf, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Kurt, Manfred, Ralf, Uli.","German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name from Middle High German <i>heide</i>, German <i>Heide</i> ‘heath, moor, open, uncultivated land’. Compare   Heath  .","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Haido</i>, a short form of any of various compound names beginning with <i>haid</i> ‘heath’ (i.e. wasteland, often with heather)."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Heath was born in 1429, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Thomas Heath, was 46 and her mother, Anna Stapleton, was 33. She married John Sheehan 17GGF about 1447, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1464, in her hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1429–1464":"1429–1464","1414–1480":"1414–1480","1415–1464":"1415–1464","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1425–1480":"1425–1480","1453–1547":"1453–1547","1383–1439":"1383–1439","1397–Female":"1397–Surnud","1383":"1383","7 November 1439":"7. november 1439","1480":"1480","1547":"1547","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1414":"1414","abt 1447":"umbes 1447","1422":"1422","1453":"1453","1464":"1464","1397":"1397","1430":"1430","1429":"1429","1439":"1439","Sheen Place, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Little Wenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Little Wenham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1429–1464":"1429–1464","1414–1480":"1414–1480","1415–1464":"1415–1464","1430–Male":"1430–Kuollut","1425–1480":"1425–1480","1453–1547":"1453–1547","1383–1439":"1383–1439","1397–Female":"1397–Kuollut","1383":"1383","7 November 1439":"7. marraskuuta 1439","1480":"1480","1547":"1547","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1414":"1414","abt 1447":"noin 1447","1422":"1422